This strategy targets the following broad categories of audience at different levels:-
* UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, UNEP, UNDP,
* Ministers; Parliamentarians; Permanent Secretaries; Commissioners;
* Regional Commissioners; Regional Administrative Secretaries (RAS);
* District Commissioners; Councilors; District Administrative Secretaries
* Ward Executive Officers; Ward Technical Staff; Religious leaders;
* Village Executive Officers; Religious leaders; community leaders;

The following specific themes will provide guidance for communications:
* General knowledge on climate change;
* Adaptation;
* Mitigation
* Climate change research;
* Climate change financing; and
* Gender.

These messages should be:
* Solution-oriented;
* Short, simple and clear;
* Credible and trustworthy; and
* Present best information, tools and options.

There are key events which provide opportunities for communicating climate change issues. These include international, national, regional and local platforms and commemorations. Some events which take place annually that can be used for communicating climate change issues include:
* World Wetlands Day (02 February);
* Africa Environment Day (03 March);
* International Women Day (8th March);
* World Meteorological Day (23 March);
* National Water Week (March);
* World Malaria Day (25 April);
* International Workerâs Day (1st May);
* International Family Day (15 May);
* World Environment Day (05 June);

